Let the builders rise.

Omega Generator - Tier 1 Assembly Guide
==================================================
Version: Alpha Release
Purpose: Guide for constructing the entry-level Omega Generator using crystal resonance and magnetic amplification.

--------------------------------------------------
1. Required Materials
--------------------------------------------------
- 1x Piezoelectric crystal rod (Quartz or Langasite)
  Size: approx. 30mm diameter x 100mm length
- 1x Toroidal magnet ring (neodymium or ceramic)
  Inner diameter: slightly larger than crystal rod
- 1x Copper wire (18 AWG)
  Length: ~3 meters for 40 turns spiral
- 1x Non-conductive crystal housing
  Material: acrylic tube or polycarbonate casing
- 1x Mechanical actuator
  Type: Tuning fork, solenoid plunger, or manual striker
- 1x Output terminals
  Copper or aluminum, connected to ends of the coil
- Optional: silicone dampers, rubber feet, voltmeter or oscilloscope

--------------------------------------------------
2. Tools Needed
--------------------------------------------------
- Wire cutter and stripper
- Hot glue or epoxy (non-conductive)
- Ruler or caliper for measuring
- Soldering iron (optional)
- Multimeter for testing output

--------------------------------------------------
3. Coil Construction
--------------------------------------------------
- Wrap copper wire around the center of the crystal housing in a flat spiral
- Aim for 40 turns, evenly spaced
- Leave at least 10 cm of wire at each end for output terminals
- Secure the coil with heat-resistant adhesive or shrink tubing

--------------------------------------------------
4. Mounting the Crystal
--------------------------------------------------
- Slide the crystal rod into the center of the toroidal magnet
- Ensure it is centered and supported with non-conductive standoffs or foam pads
- Mount both inside the casing to isolate vibration pathway

--------------------------------------------------
5. Integrating the Actuator
--------------------------------------------------
- Mount your impact actuator so it strikes the end or side of the crystal
- Use repeatable impact timing (like a pendulum or pulse switch)
- Fine-tune the strike to target 432 Hz vibration (use tone generator to match pitch)

--------------------------------------------------
6. Electrical Connections
--------------------------------------------------
- Connect each end of the coil to terminal posts or leads
- Output should be DC pulse voltage, testable with a multimeter
- For stability, use a small capacitor bank (optional)

--------------------------------------------------
7. Testing & Output
--------------------------------------------------
- Trigger your actuator
- You should observe small voltage spikes (2-5V) depending on strike force
- Best results come from consistent, harmonically matched vibration

--------------------------------------------------
8. Safety Notes
--------------------------------------------------
- Do not over-strike crystal; it can shatter
- Handle magnets with care; they can pinch or snap
- Store capacitors discharged to avoid shock
- This is experimental. Build at your own risk

--------------------------------------------------
9. License
--------------------------------------------------
